widgets_values: Night, moonlight, bioluminescence (body self-emission), rim light & side light, cool tone, high contrast, extreme wide shot → close-up (continuous), right-weighted composition, low-angle & top-down linkage. In fog, a woman sheathed in silver-blue streams stands in profile; the camera dives from high and pushes into a facial close-up as she raises her arms and steps in, fingers joined as a sword hand, wrists externally rotate tracing concentric circles before her chest. The camera moves with her arms in synchronicity, tilting slightly as the wrists rotate, smoothly following the intricate hand gestures.

The camera rides her shoulder line in a 270° large-radius orbit upward; she switches mudras—backs of hands together, tiger’s mouths interlocked, thumb pressing the second phalanx of the index finger—pulling silver-blue sigil threads from her fingertips. The camera sweeps up with a fluid curve, maintaining the 270° orbit as her hands move, then it pushes forward as the sigil threads extend. The camera pierces the light tail to a seamless transition into a “dome of light”; she turns palms outward then closes them, elbows drawn in, torso pitching forward half a step, and a six-petal sigil array blooms in her palms. The camera continues to orbit, slowing as it tracks the unfolding sigil.

The camera side-tracks long with a 45° roll skimming the array’s edge as she cleaves downward, compressing it into an arc shield, then whip-flicks upward to cast a spiraling light lash that coils around her. The camera accelerates through the spiral as the whip flicks outward, shifting perspective to track the whip's movement in the air, following the arc tightly as it coils.

Final beat: the camera hard-stops on an eye close-up; she snaps thumb and middle finger, the sigil threads lock into a net, micro-pulses of light and her breathing are crisply visible. The camera slowly tightens as the threads form the net, focusing on the delicate movements of her fingers and the tiny sparks of light that pulse between them.
